Flight Data Analysis¶

by Kathy Mirzaei¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This dataset contains flight arrival and departure details for all commercial flights within the USA including cancellation and delay information. The dataset is from the most recent year the data was available which was 2008.

Observation of some of the issues in the address:

  • No easy way to identify delayed flights; so, I am going to add Delayed column to the dataset if the flight is delayed based on DepDelay data as 1 (Yes) or 0 (No) based on x>0 or x<0

  • CarrierDelay, WeatherDelay, NASDelay, SecurityDelay, LateAircraftDelay, CancellationCode have both NaN's and 0's, I am going to convert all NaN's to 0's

  • DepDelay has some missing values, looking at it revealed these flights were cancelled. [Do I want to do something here]

  • DepTime, CRSDepTime, ArrTime, CRSArrTime are of type float rather than timedate( I have observed this, but I don't think it is required to be changed. However, I have made a mental note to change them if I see it would be better).

notes to carry forward and think about: A flight delay is when an airline flight takes off and/or lands later than its scheduled time. The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) considers a flight to be delayed when it is 15 minutes later than its scheduled time. A cancellation occurs when the airline does not operate the flight at all for a certain reason. source: https://www.bts.gov/topics/airlines-and-airports/airline-time-performance-and-causes-flight-delays

The following observation can be seen from a quick analysis of the data above:

  • When ArrDelay or DepDelay is bigger or equal to 15 minutes we see data about what caused the delay in the columns of CarrierDelay, WeatherDelay, NASDelay and LateAircraftDelay. The sum of these columns is equal to the DepDelay or ArrDelay.
  • When a flight is Cancelled or diverted, we see no data related to cause of the delay.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

We have a large Airline flight performance dataset that contains 7,009,728 flights with 29 features/variables. The dataset is for the year 2008.

Some issues were found and resolved to make the dataset better for analyzing and visualizing, such as inconsistent null value and some missing usefull columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm mostly interested in figuring out the following:

  • what causes the delays?
  • when does the most delays happen? (day, month, time)
  • what types of delays happens the most?
  • what features are best for predicting whether there will be a delay for the flight or not.
  • what features are best for predicting whether the flight will be canceled or not.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think features such as Origin, Weather or any other delay reasons, Destination, Diverted flights and Carrier might have major effect in delaying or canceling a flight.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The Delayed variable was the variable I had to dig further in, at first I read about norm of delayed time, then saw that in the data that If I do not include the threshold the % of the delayed flights will be really high and seemed unusuall. I also observed that delayed reasons are only shown when DepDelay or DepArr is greater or equal to 15. Based on all these factors, I have decided to incorporate both my findings from the data, and the norm of delayed in concept and put the threshold at anyflight that is delayed more than 15 minutes.

The other variable I worked with was the cancellation. Around 2% of the flights are cancelled and this did not come accross as odd and therefore I did not perform any transformation for this data like the way I did for the Delayed data.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I had a debate whether I should change the time from minute to regular datetime format, but after going through the analysis I realized that is not necessary. However, I had that listed as things to be changed at first.

I added the column Delayed in which I have set the threshold to be >=15 in minutes and made the column to 0 for no delay and 1 if it was delayed.

I have excluded the outliers in the DepDelay column for better and more accurate visualization

Also I replaced the Nan's with a 0 in my features of interest.

# converting value counts to percentages, so we can see both delay yes/no and carriers in a plot:
def bar_by_column(col, against):
    flights_counts = (df_clean.groupby([col])[against]
                         .value_counts(normalize=True)
                         .rename(against+' (%)')
                         .mul(100)
                         .reset_index()
                         .sort_values(against+' (%)', ascending=False))

    plt.figure(figsize=[16,8])
    plt.yticks([])
    plt.title(col + ' vs. ' + against+' (%)')
    

    g = sb.barplot(x=col, y=against+' (%)', hue=against, data=flights_counts, palette='Blues')

    # write percentages above bars 
    for p in g.patches:
        g.annotate("%.2f" % p.get_height(), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), 
                   ha='center', fontsize=12, xytext=(0, 10), textcoords='offset points', )
    
    # change legend
    leg = g.axes.get_legend()
    labels = ['No', 'Yes']
    for t, l in zip(leg.texts, labels): t.set_text(l)
    
    # To make space for the annotations
    _ = g.set_ylim(0, 110)

# Get percentages of delays by origing using the following function:
def get_percentages(data, col, against):
    flights_totals = (data.groupby([col])[against]
                         .value_counts(normalize=True)
                         .rename(against+' (%)')
                         .mul(100)
                         .reset_index()
                         .sort_values(against+' (%)', ascending=False))

    return flights_totals.query(against+' == 1 ')[[col, against+' (%)']]

delayed_flights_by_origin = get_percentages(df_clean, 'Origin', 'Delayed')

def scatter_by_column(data, col, against):
    plt.figure(figsize=[20,7])
    sb.scatterplot(data=data, x=col, y=against+' (%)', alpha=.5)
    plt.yticks(np.arange(0,data[against+' (%)'].max()+5,5))
    plt.grid()
    plt.title(col + ' vs. ' + against+' (%)')
    plt.xticks([]);
